article.description: Dawn Staley scored 16 points, including a pair of free throws with 14.3 seconds left, to help the Sting snap a six-game losing streak with a 67-61 win over the Liberty.
article.headline: Charlotte avoids matching worst start in team history
article.linkText: Sting snap six-game losing skid, end Liberty's hot streak
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Dawn Staley and a lengthy team meeting
helped the Charlotte Sting avoid one of the worst starts in team
history.

Staley scored 16 points, including a pair of free throws with
14.3 seconds left, and the Sting snapped a six-game losing streak
with a 67-61 win over the New York Liberty on Saturday night.

Tammy Sutton-Brown added 16 points and eight rebounds, Tangela
Smith scored 16 points and Staley finished with eight assists for
the Sting (2-9), who shot 51 percent and avoided matching the
team's worst start.

Coach Trudi Lacey called a team meeting after Thursday's
15-point home loss to San Antonio, and the gathering lasted two
hours.

"I'm the type of coach that likes input," Lacey said.
"Whatever they need me to do, I want to do it for them. Hopefully,
they have an appreciation for that."

Staley, who was benched for the final 13 minutes of Charlotte's
loss to the Silver Stars, converted two free throws to give the
Sting a 65-61 lead. New York's Becky Hammon missed a 3-point
attempt on the next possession.

Staley thinks the meeting was a good idea.

"You want to communicate and try to find solutions to problems
on the floor," Staley said. "I think Trudi wanted us to produce a
little bit more and we stepped up to the challenge."

Shameka Christon scored a career-high 19 points, and Ann Wauters
added 16 points for the Liberty (5-5), who had won three straight.

"Charlotte was a lot more aggressive," Liberty coach Pat Coyle
said. "When you're 1-9, there's nothing you can do but play
harder. Tonight, they played harder."

New York rallied from a nine-point, first-half deficit, tying
the game on Christon's 3-pointer with 11:43 left.

Charlotte responded with a 13-5 run, including five straight
points after Lacey picked up a technical foul for arguing a foul
call. Smith's steal and layup made it 53-45 with 7:39 left.

"In the meeting, the players told me they didn't know why I had
become so calm," Lacey said. "Maybe they feed off of that.
Whatever it takes."

The Liberty cut the deficit to two points three times, including
63-61 with 15.8 seconds left.

The Sting hit 10 of their first 17 shots and charged to a 22-14
lead. Smith, who scored 10 first-half points, scored on a runner in
the lane to make it 26-17 with 4:50 left.

Staley's 3-pointer from the left corner in the final second of
the half gave Charlotte a 32-26 lead.

"I have a lot of respect for Dawn and what she has done for the
game," Hammon said. "It was a matter of each us trying to get our
teams to win. I didn't do it, but she did."
